{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a007","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"TABLE_ROW","verbatim":"| 4 | RSV1230 | IS | RSV1230-011 | 4 | 13668 | CYKCSCLL | Cytokine-secreting Cells | INTERFERON GAMMA | WITH STIMULATING AGENT | RSV-STIMULATING AGENT | STUDY VACCINE-RELATED IMMUNOGENICITY | CELLULAR IMMUNITY | 280.5 | SFC/10^6 PBMC | 280.5 | SFC/10^6 PBMC | | ELISPOT | | VISIT 1 | 2017-08-27 |","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"middle","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The next 2 examples show data from microneutralization and opsonophagocytic killing (OPK) assays, which are used to measure vaccine efficacy and immunoprotectivity.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"Example 8","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":3,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"In vaccine studies, microneutralization assays are commonly used in assays to quantify viral-specific neutralizing antibodies in a subject's specimen that can block viral infection in vitro, and therefore provide a measure of vaccine efficacy.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"A neutralizing antibody is an antibody that binds to, blocks, and prevents non-cell infecting cells.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"When immunizing a subject with a vaccine, the hope is that the vaccine will induce antiviral and humoral-protective antibody responses in the subject; with an effective vaccine, the quantity of virus-specific antibodies that are able to block viral infection are increased.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"To test the efficacy of a vaccine, a microneutralization test is performed by adding a vaccinated subject's serum and the virus of study interest to cell cultures in vitro.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"If neutralizing antibodies are present in the subject's serum post-vaccination, those antibodies will bind, block, and prevent the virus from infecting cells in the culture plates.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The neutralization tier is the specific dilution of the antibody that blocks viral infection of the cells.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The 50% neutralization tier (also known as NT50), in the context of microneutralization assays, is defined as the antiviral antibody tier that blocks 50% of viral infection of the cells.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Note: Some users may represent the 50% neutralization tier as \"[IC50\" tier or other test descriptors. CDISC recommends mapping all such values in the ISTEST/ISTESTCD.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0238_a018","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":238,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"NHOID is populated with respiratory syncytial virus because this microorganism is the subject of the vaccine efficacy test.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a001","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"NOTE","verbatim":"NHOID, defined by the Non-host Organism Identifiers (OI) domain, should be used to map microorganisms that have been either experimentally determined in the course of a study or are previously known (e.g., In other words, NHOID is used when the study subject is the microorganism, and when the microorganism is present in the testing sample. In vaccine efficacy studies, a subject's post-immunization sera is often incubated with a microbial strain of interest, where the functionalities of the vaccine-induced antibodies are measured through whether the antibodies can effectively stop (from infection), neutralize, and kill the study microorganism of interest, in vitro. Examples of such tests include microneutralization, hemagglutination inhibition, and opsonophagocytic-killing assays. These are tests that measure the direct effect of the antimicrobial antibodies on the microorganism; therefore, said microorganism is the study subject and should be mapped to NHOID.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a002","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"This example uses data from the same RSV vaccine study, where the subject is being vaccinated with a viral vector containing RSV.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a003","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"top","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The subject is tested before (baseline) and after vaccination (visits 1 and 2) to investigate whether the anti-RSV antibodies present in the subject's serum also have the ability to neutralize RSV infection in vitro.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
