{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a008","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"HEADING","verbatim":"Example 9","heading_level":6,"sibling_index":4,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a009","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"In vaccine trials, the OPK assay is used as a correlate for immunoprotectivity against antigens, by measuring the functional capacities of vaccine-induced antibodies.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a010","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"Typically, this test is performed by incubating a subject's post-immunization sera with the bacterial strain of interest, phagocytes, and complement proteins.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a011","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"If antibacterial, functional antibodies are present in the subject's serum, will bind to the bacteria together with complement proteins.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a012","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"This subsequently targets the bacteria for opsonization, the ingestion and destruction of invading non-self agents by phagocytes.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a013","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"With vaccination, the quantity of bacterial-specific, functional antibodies are increased, leading to a decreased number of viable bacterial cells in the presence of phagocytes, functional antibodies, and complement.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a014","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The assay read-out is expressed in by the opsonization index, which is calculated using linear interpolation of the serum dilution containing functional antibody killing the desired percentage (usually 50%) of the bacteria, using a specified algorithm.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a015","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"NHOID is populated with Staphylococcus aureus 04-02981 because this strain of S. aureus is the subject of the vaccine efficacy test.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a016","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"NOTE","verbatim":"NHOID, defined by the Non-host Organism Identifiers (OI) domain, should be used to map microorganisms that have been either experimentally determined in the course of a study or are previously known (e.g., In other words, NHOID is used when the study subject is the microorganism, and when the microorganism is present in the testing sample. In vaccine efficacy studies, a subject's post-immunization sera is often incubated with a microbial strain of interest, where the functionalities of the vaccine-induced antibodies are measured through whether the antibodies can effectively stop (from infection), neutralize, and kill the study microorganism of interest, in vitro. Examples of such tests include microneutralization, hemagglutination inhibition, and opsonophagocytic-killing assays. These are tests that measure the direct effect of the antimicrobial antibodies on the microorganism; therefore, said microorganism is the study subject and should be mapped to NHOID.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a017","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"In this vaccine-study example, the subject is vaccinated with a vector containing S. aureus-epitope X (note: epitope X is an example, refer to controlled terminology for standard terms associated with ISBDAGNT).","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a018","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The subject is tested before (baseline) and after vaccination (visits 1 and 2) to investigate whether the vaccine-induced functional antibodies drive efficient complement deposition and subsequent opsonophagocytic killing of S. aureus, in vitro.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"ig34_p0239_a019","source":"SDTMIG_v3.4","page":239,"page_region":"bottom","parent_section":"§6.3.5.5 Immunogenicity Specimen Assessments (IS)","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"The assay read-out is expressed by the opsonization index (ISTEST/ISTESTCD), which is a unit-less test.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"oh-my-claudecode:writer","prompt_version":"P0_writer_pdf_v1.2","ts":"2026-04-26T00:00:00Z"}}
